Stakeholders of the All Progressives Congress (APC) in Rivers State, have began moves to reconcile the two major factions in the party, led by Minister of Transportation, Rt. Hon. Chibuike Rotimi Amaechi and Senator Magnus Ngei Abe. Speaking during a stakeholders’ meeting in Port Harcourt yesterday, former member of the House of Representatives, Hon. Igo Aguma, expressed regrets that efforts were being made by some APC members in the state to scuttle the peace move. In attendance at the meeting were former members of the National Assembly, former members of the Rivers State House of Assembly and former political appointees. Aguma said: “The invitation to this meeting clearly that it is not a formal meeting of APC members. The invitation cut across both factions of the APC in Rivers State. “As conveners of this meeting, we have been trying our best to see how we can bring both factions of the party together.” Earlier in his opening remarks, convener of the meeting and former member of the House of Representatives, Hon. Emma Deeyah, dismissed insinuations that they were being sponsored by Rivers State governor, Nyesom Ezenwo Wike. Deeyah stated that the only way out of the present condition of APC in the state, is for the leaders of the party to go into dialogue first before talking about organising congress. He said the caretaker committee set up by the national leadership of the party is unconstitutional, as former elected lawmakers are statutory members of the State Executive Council of the party.